","1399–Male":"1399–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1274–Female":"1274–Deceased","1404":"1404","about 1294":"about 1294","1368":"1368","about 1380":"about 1380","Abt 1399":"about 1399","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","Arlington, Devon, England":"Arlington, Devon, England",", Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Beaford, Devon, England":"Beaford, Devon, England","Arlington, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Arlington, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Worlington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): habitational name from Wormington in Gloucestershire or Berry Wormington in Stanton (also Gloucestershire). Perhaps also from Warmington in Northamptonshire. The placenames derive from an Old English personal name <i>Wyrma</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Worlington was born in 1352, in Arlington, Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Mathew Worlington, was 83 and her mother, Sara Worlington, was 78. She married William Hatch about 1380, in Beaford, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"1352–":"1352–Surnud","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1368–1404":"1368–1404","1399–Male":"1399–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1404":"1404","about 1294":"umbes 1294","1368":"1368","about 1380":"umbes 1380","Abt 1399":"umbes 1399","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","Arlington, Devon, England":"Arlington, Devon, England",", Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beaford, Devon, England":"Beaford, Devon, England","Arlington, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Arlington, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1352–":"1352–Kuollut","1352–Female":"1352–Kuollut","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1368–1404":"1368–1404","1399–Male":"1399–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1274–Female":"1274–Kuollut","1404":"1404","about 1294":"noin 1294","1368":"1368","about 1380":"noin 1380","Abt 1399":"noin 1399","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","Arlington, Devon, England":"Arlington, Devon, England",", Devonshire, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Beaford, Devon, England":"Beaford, Devon, England","Arlington, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Arlington, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1352–":"1352–Décéd